"https://medium.com/@lifeparticle/membership", "paragraph_index": 17}], "all_paragraphs": ["In recent years data visualization has become one of the primary tools for decision making in healthcare, not-for-profits, and many other sectors. By using data visualization, such as charts and maps, we can represent data graphically. It helps people to make quick judgments based on trends and patterns.", "There are many data visualization tools available on the internet. Out of the extensive list of these tools, plotly.js is one of them. It\u2019s a JavaScript open-source graphing library built on top of d3.js and stack.gl. This library comes with a wide variety of chart types, including 3D charts, graphs, and SVG maps.", "I\u2019ve used plotly.js to create dashboards to visualize data with interactive charts from its affluent graphing library. I prefer Plotly.js over other libraries because it\u2019s easy to use and has robust documentation. From this post, you\u2019ll learn some basic concepts and commands of plotly.js that will teach you how to visualize data.", "First, we need to add the plotly.js in the HTML file. You can either download the file or use a CDN link. Here, we will use the CDN link for convenience. After that, we need an empty DIV called test to attach the chart. Last, we need to add some JavaScript code that will draw the chart. Now save the following code inside an HTML file, like test.html.", "By loading this file on your browser, you can see a line graph like the one below. In case you do not see anything, try opening the developer console of the browser. It will help you debug the problem.", "Now let\u2019s break down the script tag to the individual pieces. First, we have the data array that contains a hash. Inside the hash, we have two key-value pairs x and y representing the value for the x-axis and y-axis. Followed by a layout hash, where we have defined the font size for the chart. The config hash is used to add extra configurations to the chart. Since we want the chart to be responsive, we set responsive to true. You can find more information about configurations here. Now we need to add our chart to an HTML element. In this case, it\u2019s a DIV with id test. Finally, we can create our chart using Plotly.newPlot method by passing the DIV DOM element, data array, layout, and config hash as arguments.", "Let\u2019s look at a few more examples.", "First, we need to define the data URL. The Plotly.d3.json method can read the JSON data from the URL provided. We can configure the chart type using the type key inside the hash of the data array. The hash also takes latitude, longitude, and hoverinfo data. The hoverinfo is used to display information when hovered over map coordinates. Here we are showing latitude and longitude information. You can find more options here. Inside the layout hash we have mapboxand margin. The options of mapbox are self-explanatory. If you are looking for more margin settings, check here. The config hash contains mapboxAccessToken and responsive key. You can get the token value from here, and we have already covered the use of responsive key.", "By running the above code on the browser, we can see a map like the one below.", "For creating a pie chart, we can configure the chart type using the type key inside the hash of the data array. We also need to define the values for each slice. To do that, we need to use values and labels as keys.", "By running the above code on the browser, we can see a pie graph like the one below.", "For creating a bar chart, we can configure the chart type using the type key inside the hash of the data array. We also need to define the values for each bar. To do that, we need to use x and y as keys.", "By running the above code on the browser, we can see a bar graph like the one below.", "For creating a bubble chart, we can configure the mode type using the mode key inside the hash of the data array. We also need to define the values for the center of each circle. To do that, we need to use x and y as keys. To set the size of the circles, use the size key. As you can see, the last circle is not visible because we didn\u2019t provide the size.", "By running the above code on the browser, we can see a bubble graph like the one below.", "Data analysis is a crucial part of many businesses. When it\u2019s easier to process data, we can improve our judgment and decision making, and it\u2019s possible when we have an effective way to display data. Plotly.js is a great tool to achieve that commercially. It can help you find hidden insights otherwise difficult to detect using the traditional approach. I hope this post will help you to get started with the plotly.js.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Computer Engineer (https://linktr.ee/lifeparticle).One day I\u2019ll write a book. Support me by becoming a Medium member https://medium.com/@lifeparticle/membership"], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F46933e1bbd29&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fhow-to-use-plotly-js-for-data-visualization-46933e1bbd29&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fhow-to-use-plotly-js-for-data-visualization-46933e1bbd29&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedi